# Free APIs for per-volume manga and light novel cover images

**The most practical free cascade for ISBN-based manga cover lookups across all three markets is: openBD + Rakuten Books for Japanese 978-4 ISBNs, VLB/MVB + Google Books for German 978-3 ISBNs, and Hardcover + Google Books + Open Library for English ISBNs, with MangaDex as a non-ISBN multi-language fallback.** No single API solves all three markets. The manga-specific databases (AniList, Kitsu, MAL, MangaUpdates) almost universally return only *series-level* art and do **not** support ISBN lookup. The strongest finding is that **MangaDex's `/cover` endpoint** is the only mainstream manga API that returns per-volume covers with locale tags (ja/en/de/etc.) at full resolution—but it is keyed by manga UUID, not ISBN. Two important deprecations to plan around: Amazon PA-API is scheduled for shutdown on **May 15, 2026** (replaced by the Creators API), and openBD's manga coverage was sharply reduced in 2023 when JPRO restricted third-party cover redistribution, particularly hurting Shueisha and Kodansha catalogues.

This report covers every API requested plus several high-value alternatives discovered during research, with verified endpoints, authentication requirements, ISBN-lookup support, image resolution, and rate limits.

## Japanese market (978-4 ISBNs)

**Rakuten Books Total Search and openBD are the two pillars for Japanese ISBNs.** Both are free, both accept ISBN-13 directly, and they are largely complementary—Rakuten has near-complete catalog coverage but caps images at 200 px, while openBD often serves higher-resolution publisher-uploaded JPEGs but has coverage gaps after 2023.

**Rakuten Books Total Search API** (`https://openapi.rakuten.co.jp/services/api/BooksTotal/Search/20170404`) is free with an instantly-issued `applicationId` (plus newly required `accessKey`). The `isbnjan` parameter accepts any 13-digit ISBN/JAN. The response returns three image fields—`smallImageUrl` (64 px), `mediumImageUrl` (128 px), and `largeImageUrl` (200 px)—all served from `thumbnail.image.rakuten.co.jp` with a `?_ex=NxN` query parameter. **Coverage is essentially complete** across Shueisha, Kodansha, Hakusensha, Square Enix, Kadokawa, Shogakukan, and ASCII Media Works; the only real downside is the 200×200 cap. Rate limit is roughly 1 req/sec per app with no documented daily quota. Example: `https://openapi.rakuten.co.jp/services/api/BooksTotal/Search/20170404?applicationId=YOUR_ID&isbnjan=9784088831770&formatVersion=2`.

**openBD** (`https://api.openbd.jp/v1/get?isbn={isbn}`) requires no authentication, accepts batches of up to 10,000 ISBNs per request, and returns a direct cover URL at `https://cover.openbd.jp/{ISBN13}.jpg`. Cover images are publisher-uploaded JPEGs and can reach the Hanmoto-preserved size of **1764×2591 px at 350 DPI**, though served sizes vary widely (often 400–800 px). The critical caveat: in August 2023, JPRO (the publisher-data inflow source) restricted third-party redistribution, and **openBD's cover coverage for Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Hakusensha has been spotty ever since**—bibliographic JSON usually still returns, but `summary.cover` is frequently missing for those publishers. Performance is exceptional: the project benchmarks at ~20,000 req/sec with no documented hard rate limit.

**NDL Search** migrated in January 2024 from `iss.ndl.go.jp` to `ndlsearch.ndl.go.jp`. The OpenSearch endpoint (`https://ndlsearch.ndl.go.jp/api/opensearch?isbn={isbn}`) returns RSS 2.0 XML metadata but no embedded cover URLs—you must construct the thumbnail URL yourself at `https://ndlsearch.ndl.go.jp/thumbnail/{ISBN13}.jpg` (`.jpg` extension is now mandatory). Cover thumbnails are backed by JPRO, so coverage has actually *improved* since the 2024 integration but is still inconsistent for back-catalog manga. Commercial use or use of the Thumbnail API requires a free email-based application; metadata access for personal use is unrestricted.

**Amazon Japan PA-API 5.0** is theoretically free but practically gated: as of November 2025, Amazon requires **10 qualifying sales in the trailing 30 days** to maintain access (tightened from the older 3-sales rule), and the entire PA-API is scheduled for deprecation on May 15, 2026 in favor of the Creators API. Not a viable option for new hobby or non-commercial projects.

Two other Japanese services were investigated and ruled out as cover sources: **CiNii Books** (`https://ci.nii.ac.jp/books/opensearch/search?isbn=...`) returns no cover URLs of its own—its web UI actually fetches covers from openBD or Google Books. **Calil** (`https://api.calil.jp/check`) is a library-holdings aggregator with no cover-image output. **BookWalker** has no public API; community-reverse-engineered URLs like `https://c.bookwalker.jp/{id}/t_700x780.jpg` still work for older titles but break for newer hash-ID releases, and BookWalker products don't have ISBNs (they use internal UUIDs). The **Hanmoto.com API was decommissioned in November 2019** and now redirects all traffic to openBD.

## German market (978-3 ISBNs)

**No single fully-free, ToS-clean, high-coverage cover API exists for German manga.** The realistic free stack centers on the **VLB/MVB** ecosystem (which feeds every major German manga publisher's data), with Google Books and Open Library as fallbacks.

The **VLB REST API** (`https://api.vlb.de/api/v1/cover/{ISBN13}/{size}?access_token={TOKEN}`) is the official source. Sizes are `s` (~75 px), `m` (~200 px), and `l` (up to ~600 px). All major German manga publishers—**Carlsen, Egmont, Tokyopop Germany, Altraverse, Manga Cult, Panini DE, and Crunchyroll Manga DE**—feed VLB at distribution time, so coverage is essentially complete. The API requires an OAuth2 access token; commercial accounts pay licensing fees, but MVB offers a free token for libraries and non-commercial public-facing catalogs with a link-back-to-buchhandel.de requirement. **VLB explicitly forbids bulk cover-pool building**—only on-demand display caching is permitted.

The **DNB MVB redirect** (`https://portal.dnb.de/opac/mvb/cover.htm?isbn={isbn}`) is an undocumented but functional bypass that serves the same VLB image without a token, suitable for embedding via `<img src>` rather than server-side fetching. Resolution is limited to ~120 px thumbnails. For metadata, the **DNB SRU API** (`https://services.dnb.de/sru/dnb?version=1.1&operation=searchRetrieve&query=num={isbn}&recordSchema=MARC21-xml`) is CC0 and anonymous; it returns complete MARC21 records but no cover URLs in the response itself.

**Lobid.org** (`https://lobid.org/resources/search?q=isbn:{isbn}&format=json`) is also CC0 and useful for metadata cross-referencing, but its JSON-LD does not include cover image fields. **Google Books** has surprisingly good German manga coverage (it ingests VLB metadata), with most Carlsen and Egmont volumes indexed—but resolution is capped at the standard `thumbnail` (~128 px) for most German entries.

Investigation of every major German manga publisher's website revealed **no predictable ISBN-keyed cover URL pattern**. Carlsen, Egmont, Tokyopop DE, Altraverse, Manga Cult, and Panini all use slug-based product pages with CMS-generated CDN paths—covers are extractable only via `og:image` scraping of individual product pages. Retailers (Thalia, Hugendubel, buecher.de, Lehmanns) similarly lack ISBN-keyed image patterns. KNV/Libri wholesale APIs exist but are B2B paid contracts only.

## English market (US/UK ISBNs)

**Hardcover.app is the best free Goodreads replacement and the strongest first choice for English ISBNs**, with Google Books and Open Library as the established fallbacks.

**Hardcover** (`https://api.hardcover.app/v1/graphql`) uses GraphQL with a bearer token from `hardcover.app/account/api` (free signup; tokens expire annually on January 1). The `editions` table supports direct `isbn_13` and `isbn_10` lookup, and each edition has an `image { url, width, height, color }` field served from a modern Cloudinary/Imaginary CDN at typically 500 px or larger. Rate limit is 60 requests per minute with a 30-second query timeout; **tokens are backend-only and CORS-blocked from browsers**. Coverage is strong because Hardcover ingested Goodreads imports and is popular with manga readers. The major caveat is that the schema is explicitly "in flux" and could break.

**Google Books** (`https://www.googleapis.com/books/v1/volumes?q=isbn:{isbn}`) re-evaluated: the documented hierarchy is `smallThumbnail`, `thumbnail`, `small`, `medium`, `large`, `extraLarge`, but for most manga only `smallThumbnail` and `thumbnail` are returned. The well-known trick of rewriting `zoom=1` to `zoom=0` (and stripping `edge=curl`) still produces images up to ~1000 px in most cases, but community reports through 2024–2026 indicate Google has been **progressively restricting higher zoom values**—`zoom=4` and above now fail for many manga volumes where they previously worked. Treat `zoom=0` as a best-effort enhancement, not a contract.

**Open Library Covers** (`https://covers.openlibrary.org/b/isbn/{ISBN}-{S|M|L}.jpg`) re-evaluated: critical operational note—**always append `?default=false`** to receive a proper HTTP 404 for missing covers rather than the silent 1×1 blank GIF default. The rate limit is **100 requests per IP per 5 minutes for ISBN-based access**, returning HTTP 403 when exceeded. The standard workaround is to query `https://openlibrary.org/api/books?bibkeys=ISBN:...&jscmd=data` first to retrieve the numeric cover ID, then hit `/b/id/{coverID}-L.jpg`, which is **not rate-limited**. Manga coverage is volunteer-uploaded and patchy outside major series.

**ISBNdb** is paid only ($14.95/mo Basic minimum, 7-day trial), so it does not meet the free requirement. **WorldCat Search API v1 was discontinued in January 2025**, and v2 is restricted to OCLC institutional subscribers; neither version returns cover images directly. **Library of Congress** APIs serve bibliographic data but no systematic cover imagery for manga. **LibraryThing's Covers API** technically works with a free dev key (1,000 covers/day) but **returns blank gifs for most manga ISBNs**—the rich LT.com covers are sourced from Amazon and not exposed via API, making it effectively useless for this purpose. **BookBrainz** has no cover repository (a future "BB Cover Art Archive" is planned but unbuilt). **Inventaire** federates Wikidata/Open Library covers with mediocre English manga coverage. **StoryGraph** has no public API at all.

For retailer cover URLs (unofficial but stable for several major chains):

| Retailer | ISBN-keyed URL pattern | Resolution |
|---|---|---|
| Barnes & Noble | `https://prodimage.images-bn.com/pimages/{ISBN13}_p0_v1_s{W}x{H}.jpg` | Up to ~1200 px |
| Indigo (Canada) | `https://dynamic.indigoimages.ca/v1/books/books/{ISBN13}/{ISBN13}.jpg?width={W}` | Variable, reliable |
| Books-A-Million | `https://covers.booksamillion.com/covers/bam/{chunked-ISBN10}.jpg` | Lower res |
| Booktopia (AU) | `https://covers.booktopia.com.au/{size}/{ISBN13}/cover.jpg` | Up to ~600 px |

For English manga publishers directly, **only Seven Seas Entertainment** shows a partially predictable ISBN-13-prefixed filename convention in their WordPress media uploads (`/wp-content/uploads/YYYY/MM/{ISBN13}_*.jpg`)—observed consistently across 2023–2026 but not contractually guaranteed. **Viz Media, Yen Press, Kodansha USA, Dark Horse, and Square Enix Books US all use internal SKU- or slug-based filenames** with no ISBN derivation possible without scraping the product page.

## Manga-specific databases and the per-volume cover problem

This is the most surprising finding of the research: **the major manga and anime metadata APIs almost universally fail on both requirements—they don't accept ISBN and they don't return per-volume covers.**

**MangaDex is the sole exception worth integrating.** Its `/cover` endpoint (`https://api.mangadex.org/cover?manga[]={mangaId}&limit=100&order[volume]=asc`) returns one cover entity per volume per locale, with attributes `volume`, `fileName`, `locale`, and `description`. A single series like Chainsaw Man will have separate entries for Japanese vol 1 (`locale: "ja"`), German vol 1 (`locale: "de"`), and English vol 1 (`locale: "en"`). Images are served at full resolution (typically 1500–2000 px wide) from `https://uploads.mangadex.org/covers/{manga-id}/{filename}`, with optional `.512.jpg` and `.256.jpg` thumbnail variants. No authentication is required for reads; the rate limit is approximately 5 req/sec per IP. The catch is that MangaDex is keyed by its own UUID, not by ISBN—you'd need to search by title first to resolve a manga UUID, then enumerate volumes. German locale coverage is community-driven and uneven, but Japanese and English are excellent.

Every other manga database disappoints:

- **MangaUpdates v1** (`https://api.mangaupdates.com/v1`) returns only a series-level `image.url.original`. Releases are tracked per volume with publisher and group metadata, but **no per-release cover images** and no ISBN field.
- **AniList GraphQL** has only `Media.coverImage { extraLarge large medium }` at series level. No volumes sub-entity exists in the schema.
- **Kitsu**, **MyAnimeList v2**, and **Jikan** all return only `posterImage`/`main_picture` series art with `num_volumes` as a count field—no per-volume art and no ISBN lookup.
- **AniDB** is anime-only; despite community confusion, manga is not a first-class entity in its API.
- **Anime News Network's Encyclopedia API** (`https://cdn.animenewsnetwork.com/encyclopedia/api.xml`) is the dark-horse exception: per-release `<release>` blocks inside a manga's XML **do include `<isbn>` tags** for licensed English editions and sometimes per-release thumbnails. ISBN cannot be the search key (you must search by title first), and coverage is uneven, but for licensed Viz/Kodansha/Yen Press releases it's a legitimate fallback.
- **Comic Vine** has per-issue covers at multiple resolutions (`original_url` up to ~2000 px), but it does not expose ISBN as a queryable filter despite years of community requests, and its API key is non-commercial-only.
- **Grand Comics Database** offers a bi-weekly MySQL dump (CC-BY 3.0) and a beta REST API, but no `/issue/isbn/{isbn}/` endpoint; you must search by series name.
- **League of Comic Geeks**, **Anime-Planet**, **Niconico**, **pixiv**, **DLsite**, and **Bookmeter** have no public APIs—only scrapers exist.

## Recommended cascade implementation

The optimal free fallback cascade for adding to an existing Google Books / Open Library / NDL stack:

For **Japanese ISBNs (978-4)**, prioritize **Rakuten Books Total Search** (broadest publisher coverage but 200 px ceiling), then **openBD direct cover URL** (often higher resolution but degraded for Shueisha/Kodansha post-2023), then **NDL thumbnail** (improving since the 2024 JPRO integration but only ~200–400 px). For **German ISBNs (978-3)**, prioritize **VLB REST API** with a free non-commercial token (the canonical source feeding all major manga publishers), then the **DNB MVB redirect** for token-free access at thumbnail resolution, then **Google Books**, then **Open Library**. For **English ISBNs**, prioritize **Hardcover GraphQL** (modern CDN, ~500 px+, 60 req/min), then **Google Books with `zoom=0` rewrite**, then **Open Library via cover ID** (to bypass the 100/5-min ISBN rate limit), then **Barnes & Noble's `prodimage.images-bn.com` ISBN-13 pattern**, then **Indigo's `dynamic.indigoimages.ca` pattern**. Across all three markets, **MangaDex `/cover`** is a powerful supplement when ISBN→title resolution is feasible, particularly for high-resolution multi-locale per-volume art.

Three operational rules are non-negotiable across this stack: **cache aggressively** (Open Library and Hardcover both rate-limit harshly), **always use `?default=false` on Open Library cover URLs**, and **plan to migrate off Amazon PA-API before May 15, 2026** if you currently use it.

## Key takeaways

The biggest analytical insight from this research is that **per-volume cover art is a structurally underserved data type**: bibliographic APIs (Google Books, Open Library, NDL, DNB) treat each ISBN as a discrete edition and serve covers well, but they have no concept of "volume 47 of this series"; conversely, manga-specific APIs (AniList, MAL, MangaUpdates) understand series and volume counts but only catalog series-level promotional art. The intersection—per-volume, ISBN-addressable, free, and high-resolution—exists nowhere as a single service, and any production system must combine at least two of these worlds. **MangaDex is the only API that natively understands volume-level art across locales**, but its lack of ISBN keying forces a search-then-enumerate pattern that is not always reliable. The 2023–2026 industry trend is also negative: openBD lost much of its manga coverage, Amazon PA-API tightened sales requirements and announced deprecation, WorldCat v1 shut down, Goodreads remains dead, and Google Books has been quietly reducing high-resolution availability. The practical conclusion is that **a robust manga cover system in 2026 must assume any single source will fail for any given ISBN and must cascade through five or more endpoints**—and even then will not achieve 100% coverage, particularly for older volumes and recently-released light novels.